          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Make and bake",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Heat the oven to 190 degrees C fan. Melt the butter in a saucepan and ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "sweat",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpqyw15m0000k4v4uibyfs9i"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " the onions for 12 minutes until completely soft. Remove from the heat and cool for 5 minutes.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "In a large bowl, combine the sausagemeat, chestnuts, breadcrumbs, dried and fresh sage, salt, and cooled onions. Add the beaten egg and mix thoroughly. The mixture is the ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "binding",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpenr2920000tsv43y1cg67m"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " that holds the stuffing together.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Press into a buttered baking dish. Bake for 45 to 50 minutes until the top is golden-brown and the sausagemeat is cooked through. A thermometer in the centre should read 75 degrees C or above.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "troubleshooter",
          "attrs": {
            "items": [
              {
                "fix": "Use a high-meat-content sausagemeat. The fat should collect at the edges; tilt the dish and drain before serving.",
                "cause": "The sausagemeat had a very high fat content that rendered during baking.",
                "symptom": "The stuffing is greasy after baking"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Bring the stuffing to room temperature 30 minutes before baking. Check with a thermometer: 75 degrees C in the centre confirms it is safe.",
                "cause": "The dish was too deep, or the stuffing was refrigerator-cold when it went in.",
                "symptom": "The centre is still pink after 50 minutes"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Chop roughly into pieces about 1 cm. Vacuum-packed cooked chestnuts hold their shape better than fresh boiled.",
                "cause": "They were very finely chopped or over-softened during cooking.",
                "symptom": "The chestnuts are too soft and disappear into the stuffing"
              },
              {
                "fix": "The dried sage mellows more than fresh during baking. Use 1 teaspoon dried as the base and fresh as a supplement.",
                "cause": "Too much fresh sage was used without enough dried to balance.",
                "symptom": "The stuffing has a strong raw sage smell even after baking"
              }
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Variations",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Add finely grated lemon zest and a small handful of dried cranberries for a brighter, more festive flavour. A tablespoon of Worcestershire sauce stirred in adds depth. For a lighter version with less sausagemeat, reduce to 300 g and increase the chestnuts and breadcrumbs.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Where this dish lives",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Chestnut stuffing became standard British Christmas fare in the twentieth century. The wider availability of prepared sausagemeat made it practical for home cooks. Chestnuts in Britain are associated with autumn and winter, roasted on open fires and stalls from October onwards. Their pairing with sausagemeat in a stuffing is a post-war British invention.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
